[
  {
    "order": 1,
    "title": "Project Overview",
    "description": "Voxlblade is a Svelte 5 + TypeScript + Vite game damage calculator and build optimizer for a fantasy RPG. It lets players configure equipment (weapons, armor, rings, runes), select perks and guilds, then computes detailed per-hit damage breakdowns across 8+ damage types with crit, defense, buffs, and DoT analysis. The app deploys as a PWA to GitHub Pages and Vercel.",
    "nodeIds": ["document:README.md", "config:package.json", "file:vite.config.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Svelte 5 runes + TypeScript 6 with Vite 8 bundler. Single runtime dependency (@vercel/analytics) — all game logic is self-contained."
  },
  {
    "order": 2,
    "title": "Application Bootstrap",
    "description": "index.html loads src/main.ts, which mounts the root App.svelte component to a #app div and imports global CSS. Vite handles HMR and module resolution. The app is a standard SPA with no server-side rendering.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:index.html", "file:src/main.ts", "file:src/app.css"],
    "languageLesson": "Svelte 5 uses the new runes API ($state, $derived, $effect). Entry point is minimal — all orchestration lives in App.svelte."
  },
  {
    "order": 3,
    "title": "Type System Foundation",
    "description": "src/lib/types.ts is the most-imported file (fan-in: 16). It defines stat keys, percent stats, damage type colors/priority, scaling-to-boost mappings, upgrade logic, and proc coefficient helpers. Every calculation module and UI component depends on these shared types and constants.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/lib/types.ts", "file:src/lib/constants.ts", "file:src/lib/utils.ts", "file:src/lib/uiConstants.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Centralized type constants pattern: types.ts holds both TypeScript types AND runtime lookup maps (DAMAGE_TYPE_COLORS, SCALING_TO_BOOST, etc.). This avoids circular dependencies while keeping type-safe access."
  },
  {
    "order": 4,
    "title": "Constants System",
    "description": "The constants directory contains 15+ focused modules organized by game domain: boosts, buffs, damage-types, defensive, dot-damage, draconic, heals, perks, rune-base-damage, stat-conversions, storage, and thresholds. Each module exports plain numeric constants consumed by the engine and data layers.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/lib/constants/index.ts", "file:src/lib/constants/boosts.ts", "file:src/lib/constants/damage-types.ts", "file:src/lib/constants/defensive.ts", "file:src/lib/constants/perks.ts", "file:src/lib/constants/storage.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Barrel re-export pattern: constants/index.ts re-exports all sub-modules, so consumers can import from 'constants' or 'constants/boosts' depending on granularity needs."
  },
  {
    "order": 5,
    "title": "Game Data Layer",
    "description": "11 JSON data files define every game entity: 10 races, 6 guilds with 3 ranks each, 200+ perks, 50+ armor sets, 35 rings, 41 runes, 51 enchantments, and weapon parts (40+ blades, handles, gloves, essences). These are loaded at runtime by engine/data/ accessor modules that provide typed lookup functions like getRace(), getPerk(), getBlade().",
    "nodeIds": ["config:src/data/races.json", "config:src/data/guilds.json", "config:src/data/perks.json", "config:src/data/armors.json", "config:src/data/enchantments.json", "config:src/data/blades.json", "config:src/data/handles.json", "config:src/data/rings.json", "config:src/data/runes.json", "file:src/lib/engine/data/character.ts", "file:src/lib/engine/data/equipment.ts", "file:src/lib/engine/data/weapons.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Data accessor pattern: engine/data/ modules wrap JSON imports with typed getter functions (getRace, getPerk, etc.), isolating data shape changes behind a stable API."
  },
  {
    "order": 6,
    "title": "Build Orchestration Engine",
    "description": "src/lib/engine/build.ts is the highest fan-out file (12 imports) — the central orchestrator. calcBuild() runs the full pipeline: accumulateEquipment() → finalizePerks() → applyStatBoostPerks() → calcCDR() → calcBoosts() → calcCrit() → computeBuffs() → deriveResults(). It coordinates weapon merging, enchantment application, shrine bonuses, and produces the final damage result object.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/lib/engine/build.ts", "file:src/lib/engine.ts", "file:src/lib/engine/weapon.ts", "file:src/lib/engine/enchant.ts", "file:src/lib/engine/shrine.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Pipeline orchestration pattern: build.ts is a pure-function pipeline with no UI dependencies. Each step (accumulate, finalize, calcBoosts, deriveResults) is a separate function, making the flow traceable."
  },
  {
    "order": 7,
    "title": "Buff and Debuff Processing",
    "description": "BuffData.ts (1600+ lines) is the largest data module. assembleActiveBuffs() is the master pipeline: collects buffs from perks, weapon arts, and racial effects → applies perk modifiers (specific, generic, bastion, trickster) → processes toxin transfer and tailwind conversion → applies cauterize conversion. Supporting modules handle draconic infusions, auto-debuffs from perks, and combat effects (weakness, shatter, sticky).",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/data/BuffData.ts", "file:src/data/draconicBuffs.ts", "file:src/data/draconicRunes.ts", "file:src/data/draconicColorEffects.ts", "file:src/data/perkAutoDebuffs.ts", "file:src/data/debuffCombatEffects.ts", "file:src/data/stanceOverlays.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "The buff system uses a factory + modifier pipeline: raw buffs are collected from multiple sources, then each modifier function transforms the buff array in sequence. This is similar to middleware chains in web frameworks."
  },
  {
    "order": 8,
    "title": "Damage Calculation Subsystems",
    "description": "Several specialized modules handle distinct damage mechanics: crit.ts computes crit chance/damage with proc-weighted averages; defense.ts resolves damage reduction from armor and perks; damageTypeResolve.ts handles fire→air→magic conversion chains; DoTDamage.ts computes bleed/burn/poison ticks; HealBoost.ts aggregates healing modifiers; Perkbasedmg.ts defines perk-triggered abilities with HP gates.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/lib/crit.ts", "file:src/lib/defense.ts", "file:src/lib/damageTypeResolve.ts", "file:src/data/DoTDamage.ts", "file:src/data/HealBoost.ts", "file:src/data/Perkbasedmg.ts", "file:src/data/selfDamagePerks.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Each subsystem is independently testable: crit, defense, and damage-type resolution are pure functions with no side effects. The HP gate pattern in Perkbasedmg.ts uses a guard clause returning undefined when conditions aren't met."
  },
  {
    "order": 9,
    "title": "State Management and Persistence",
    "description": "src/lib/store.ts uses Svelte writable stores for the active build state and computed results. Actions (setGuild, setEnchantment, clearBuild) mutate the store. localStorage persistence is handled via constants/storage.ts keys and BuildSaves.svelte, which provides save/load/export/import with named slots, confirm-delete UX, and file import. Toast notifications use a separate store with auto-dismiss.",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/lib/store.ts", "file:src/lib/stores/toast.ts", "file:src/BuildSaves.svelte", "file:src/lib/constants/storage.ts"],
    "languageLesson": "Svelte stores + localStorage pattern: the store exposes mutation actions rather than direct set() calls. Persistence is layered: store → localStorage read on load, store → JSON.stringify on save."
  },
  {
    "order": 10,
    "title": "Root Component and UI Architecture",
    "description": "App.svelte (3699 lines) is the root orchestrator managing all build state and rendering equipment modals (race, guild, armor, weapon parts), weapon art selection, buff/debuff lists, and damage analysis tabs. DamageAnalyzer.svelte (6565 lines) is the largest component, computing full damage analysis by integrating all engine subsystems. The UI uses a modal system (Modal.svelte + specialized modals) with search/filter capabilities (TagFilter, StatFilter, WeaponStatFilter).",
    "nodeIds": ["file:src/App.svelte", "file:src/DamageAnalyzer.svelte", "file:src/lib/Modal.svelte", "file:src/lib/modals/RaceModal.svelte", "file:src/lib/modals/GuildModal.svelte", "file:src/lib/modals/WeaponPartModal.svelte", "file:src/ModalSearchHeader.svelte", "file:src/TagFilter.svelte", "file:src/StatFilter.svelte"],
    "languageLesson": "Component composition: small reusable pieces (Modal, Highlight, CritIcon, MountIcon) compose into large orchestrators (App → DamageAnalyzer → BaseDamageCalc → ScalingBreakdownRow). The filter system uses a three-state toggle pattern (off/include/exclude) via createFilterActions factory."
  },
  {
    "order": 11,
    "title": "Deployment and CI/CD",
    "description": "The project deploys to both GitHub Pages (via .github/workflows/static.yml using Node.js 24, npm build, and actions/deploy-pages) and Vercel (via vercel.json with Vite preset and PWA caching headers). Fallow (.fallowrc.json) provides duplicate detection and security analysis. The PWA uses StaleWhileRevalidate caching for offline support.",
    "nodeIds": ["pipeline:.github/workflows/static.yml", "config:vercel.json", "config:.fallowrc.json", "config:fallow-output.json"],
    "languageLesson": "Dual deployment: GitHub Pages for open-source hosting, Vercel for production. Vite PWA plugin auto-generates the service worker with caching strategies defined in vite.config.ts."
  }
]